#
#  @stricli/core distinctive features:
#    - TAGGED-UNION FLAG SCHEMA via `kind` discriminant:
#      `kind: 'boolean'` (bool flag), `kind: 'parsed'` (value
#      flag with custom `parse: (str) => T` parser function),
#      `kind: 'enum'` (value flag with `values: [...] as const`
#      tuple of allowed strings — TypeScript narrows the parsed
#      type to the union of those strings)
#    - POSITIONAL SCHEMA via tagged-union too: `kind: 'array'`
#      (variadic with min/max counts), `kind: 'tuple'` (fixed-
#      arity tuple), `kind: 'object'` (named positional set)
#    - LAZY COMMAND LOADING via `loader: async () => import('./impl')`
#      — command body is dynamically imported ONLY when its
#      subcommand is matched (faster CLI startup for large
#      command trees)
#    - SEPARATE LIFECYCLE: buildCommand (per-command) →
#      buildRouteMap (subcommand tree) → buildApplication
#      (versioning/context) → run(app, argv) — modular
#      architecture lets each step be tested independently
#    - CONTEXT INJECTION via `this: CommandContext` parameter —
#      handlers receive a typed context with `process` (process
#      ref), `env` (env vars), `logger`, custom services
#      injected by the caller via LocalContext extension
#    - ALIAS MAP — `aliases: { i: 'init', b: 'build' }` in
#      buildRouteMap registers short-form subcommand aliases
#    - HIDDEN ROUTES — `hideRoute: { __cli_bash_complete: true }`
#      in buildRouteMap excludes routes from --help (used for
#      shell-completion shim commands)
#    - SEPARATE @stricli/auto-complete COMPANION PACKAGE —
#      `buildInstallCommand`/`buildUninstallCommand` from
#      @stricli/auto-complete generates `xs-dev install` /
#      `xs-dev uninstall` shim commands that install/remove
#      bash/zsh/fish completion scripts on the user's system
#    - PROPOSE COMPLETIONS API — `proposeCompletions(app, argv,
#      context)` returns suggested completions for the current
#      argv prefix; powers the bash/zsh completion shell scripts
#    - STRICT TYPE-INFERENCE from schema to handler:
#      `flags: { mode: { kind: 'enum', values: ['a', 'b'] as const } }`
#      → handler's `flags.mode` is typed as `'a' | 'b'` literal
#      union, not just `string`
#    - ZERO RUNTIME DEPENDENCIES — Bloomberg explicitly designed
#      stricli to ship without ANY transitive deps (no chalk, no
#      enquirer, no parsed-helpers) so it can be safely embedded
#      in enterprise environments with strict dep-audit rules
#    - INSPIRED BY oclif (Heroku/Salesforce class-based) — but
#      with FUNCTION-BUILDER rather than class-based commands,
#      and ZERO transitive deps vs oclif's larger footprint
#  Distinct from R236 commander (TJ chained-builder), R237 oclif
#  (Heroku/Salesforce CLASS-BASED with decorators — @stricli/core
#  is oclif's spiritual successor for Bloomberg's TS tooling, but
#  function-builder vs class-based), yargs (Bash-style — npm/
#  jest), R398 meow (Sindre zero-config), R399 minimist, R400 cac,
#  R403 clipanion (Yarn's class-based with `@Command()`
#  decorators — clipanion is the CLOSEST RELATIVE in enterprise-
#  scale TS positioning; both are aimed at large-scale CLI
#  applications but clipanion via decorators, stricli via
#  function-builder), R406 vercel/arg, R409 mri, R412 citty (UnJS
#  DECLARATIVE-SCHEMA), R415 cmd-ts (parser-combinator algebra),
#  R418 gluegun (Infinite Red TOOLBOX PATTERN), R422 cleye
#  (privatenumber's type-constructor-as-type-spec), R428
#  @caporal/core (Mathieu Robin's enterprise framework with
#  integrated logger), R432 @effect/cli (Effect-TS algebraic
#  effect system).  TypeScript-Node documented libraries so far:
#  commander, oclif, yargs, meow, minimist, cac, clipanion, arg,
#  mri, sade, citty, cmd-ts, gluegun, cleye, @caporal/core,
#  @effect/cli, @stricli/core (this round)... 18 total.  @stricli/
#  core's distinguishing feature vs all other TS-Node libs:
#  @stricli/core is the ONLY one BACKED BY BLOOMBERG LP (a major
#  financial-services firm) and explicitly designed for ZERO
#  RUNTIME DEPENDENCIES.  @stricli/core's approach: ENTERPRISE-
#  GRADE TYPESCRIPT-FIRST framework with `buildCommand` per-
#  command builder + `buildRouteMap` subcommand tree + `build
#  Application` version+metadata wrapper + `run(app, argv, ctx)`
#  executor + TAGGED-UNION SCHEMA via `kind: 'boolean'/'parsed'/
#  'enum'` flag discriminant + `kind: 'array'/'tuple'/'object'`
#  positional discriminant + LAZY command loading via `loader:
#  async () => import(...)` for fast startup + CONTEXT INJECTION
#  via `this: CommandContext` + ALIAS MAP for short subcommand
#  forms + SEPARATE `@stricli/auto-complete` package for
#  bash/zsh/fish completion generation + `proposeCompletions`
#  API for shell-completion shells + STRICT TYPE-INFERENCE from
#  schema to handler (enum `values: [...] as const` → handler
#  param typed as literal union) + ZERO RUNTIME DEPENDENCIES
#  (Bloomberg dep-audit compatible) + INSPIRED BY oclif but
#  function-builder vs class-based — corpus's **first documented
#  Bloomberg-LP-backed enterprise TypeScript-Node CLI library**.
#  Brings cross-language CLI library taxonomy variant count to
#  172; TypeScript-Node ecosystem now has 18 documented CLI
#  libraries — RE-TAKING THE SOLO LEAD as the MOST-DOCUMENTED CLI
#  LANGUAGE in the cross-language taxonomy ahead of Rust (17)
#  and Go (17).
#
#  Surface (verbatim from `src/app.ts` buildRouteMap + per-
#  subcommand `src/commands/*.ts` buildCommand definitions):
#
#  Usage:
#    xs-dev <subcommand> [options]
#
#  Subcommands:
#    build                          Build a Moddable JS app for a
#                                   target device (or simulator)
#    clean                          Clean Moddable build artifacts
#                                   for a target
#    debug                          Launch xsbug debugger attached
#                                   to running device
#    doctor (aliases: dr, info)     Diagnose Moddable SDK
#                                   installation issues (host
#                                   toolchain check, environment
#                                   var check, USB device check)
#    include                        Add a Moddable manifest include
#                                   to current project
#    init                           Initialize a new Moddable JS
#                                   project (scaffolds main.js +
#                                   manifest.json)
#    remove                         Remove a Moddable component or
#                                   tool installation
#    run                            Build + flash + run a Moddable
#                                   app on a target device (the
#                                   primary workflow)
#    scan                           Scan for connected target
#                                   devices (USB enumeration)
#    setup                          Download and build Moddable
#                                   tooling for various platform
#                                   targets (ESP8266, ESP32, Pico,
#                                   nRF52, Zephyr, WASM, host)
#    teardown                       Remove a previously-installed
#                                   Moddable target toolchain
#    update                         Update Moddable SDK to latest
#                                   release or specified branch
#
#  Common options (per-subcommand, varies):
#    --help, -h                     Show subcommand help
#    --version, -v                  Show xs-dev version (top-level
#                                   only; auto from versionInfo)
#
#  xs-dev setup options (representative for documenting flag
#  surface — most subcommands have similar device/branch/release
#  options):
#    --device <DEVICE>              Target device (esp8266 / esp32
#                                   / pico / wasm / nrf52 / zephyr
#                                   / mac / linux / win); inferred
#                                   from host platform when absent
#    --list-devices                 Print list of available target
#                                   devices and prompt selection
#                                   (interactive)
#    --tool <TOOL>                  Run a specific Moddable tool
#                                   (currently: ejectfix)
#    --branch <BRANCH>              Moddable SDK git branch to
#                                   install (e.g. main, public-
#                                   release-2024-09)
#    --release <RELEASE>            Moddable SDK release version
#                                   (default: latest)
#    --source-repo <URL>            Custom Moddable source repo URL
#                                   (default: https://github.com/
#                                   Moddable-OpenSource/moddable)
#    --interactive                  Enable interactive prompts
#                                   (default: true; --no-interactive
#                                   for CI/non-TTY use)
#
#  Examples:
#    xs-dev doctor                                        # Diagnose installation
#    xs-dev dr                                            # Same (alias)
#    xs-dev info                                          # Same (alias)
#    xs-dev setup --device esp32                          # Install ESP32 toolchain
#    xs-dev setup --device pico --release latest          # Pico setup
#    xs-dev setup --list-devices                          # Interactive device picker
#    xs-dev init my-app                                   # Scaffold new project
#    xs-dev run --device esp32 --port /dev/ttyUSB0        # Build + flash + run
#    xs-dev build --device wasm                           # Build for WebAssembly
#    xs-dev debug                                         # Launch xsbug debugger
#    xs-dev clean --device esp32                          # Clean build artifacts
#    xs-dev scan                                          # Scan for connected devices
#    xs-dev update                                        # Update Moddable SDK
#    xs-dev teardown --device esp32                       # Remove ESP32 toolchain
#    xs-dev --version                                     # Print xs-dev version
#    xs-dev --help                                        # Show help
#
#  Dup-skipped neighbors during hunt (in corpus or smaller user base,
#  also @stricli/core users):
